diff --git a/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md b/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md
new file mode 100644
index 00000000..c6c212fb
--- /dev/null
+++ b/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md
@@ -0,0 +1,85 @@
+# Why You Cannot Fix `glibc` Vulnerabilities via Code Patching in Containers
+
+## Overview: What Is `glibc`?
+
+`glibc` (GNU C Library) is the core C runtime used by most Linux distributions. It provides low-level system functionality such as:
+
+- System calls
+- Threading (via NPTL)
+- Memory allocation
+- Internationalization
+
+Due to its critical role, `glibc` is tightly coupled with the OS and is not easily replaceable or patchable—especially in containers.
+
+---
+
+## Why Vulnerabilities in `glibc` Are Often Not Fixable in Containers
+
+Security scanners (Trivy, Grype, etc.) flag vulnerabilities based on:
+
+- Package metadata (e.g., `libc6` version)
+- Public security feeds (NVD, Debian Tracker)
+
+However, these scans often generate **false positives** because they:
+
+- Ignore runtime behavior or build configuration
+- Flag packages even if the vulnerable code is unused or removed
+- Don’t account for upstream decisions to not treat certain CVEs as security issues
+
+Manually patching or replacing `glibc` can:
+
+- Break containerized applications
+- Violate system-level ABI compatibility
+- Introduce instability or undefined behavior
+
+---
+
+# ⚠️ CVE Breakdown
+
+Below are known `glibc` CVEs that are often flagged but are either **not exploitable**, **false positives**, or **not treated as security issues upstream**.
+
+---
+
+## 📌 CVE-2019-1010022 – Mitigation Bypass in NPTL
+
+- **Component:** NPTL (Native POSIX Thread Library)
+- **Issue:** Stack guard mitigation bypass via stack buffer overflow
+- **Impact:** Theoretical ability to bypass stack protections
+- **Upstream Status:** ❗ Not considered a security vulnerability  
+  → [Upstream Bugzilla #22850](https://sourceware.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=22850)
+
+### Vulnerable Versions (Debian)
+| Release              | Version               | Status     |
+|----------------------|------------------------|------------|
+| bullseye             | 2.31-13+deb11u11       | Vulnerable |
+| bookworm             | 2.36-9+deb12u10        | Vulnerable |
+| sid/trixie           | 2.41-9                 | Vulnerable |
+
+### Why You Can't Fix This
+- No official patch exists
+- Not treated as a real-world exploit
+- Updating glibc won’t eliminate the flag
+- Replacing glibc in containers is unsafe
+
+**✅ Recommendation:** Mark as a known false positive. No action needed.
+
+---
+
+## Summary
+
+- `glibc` is not designed to be patched or replaced within containers.
+- Many CVEs flagged by scanners are:
+  - **False positives**
+  - **Non-exploitable**
+  - **Not security-relevant**
+- Attempting to "fix" them can cause serious stability issues.
+
+**📌 Best Practice:** Document these CVEs, understand their context, and only act on legitimate, exploitable vulnerabilities.
+
+---
+
+## References
+
+- [Debian Security Tracker](https://security-tracker.debian.org/)
+- [NVD - National Vulnerability Database](https://nvd.nist.gov/)
+- [GNU libc Bugzilla](https://sourceware.org/bugzilla/)
Description: Fix CVE-2026-5450 one-byte heap overflow in scanf %mc / %mC
 When enlarging the allocated buffer for the %mc or %mC scanf conversion,
 __vfscanf_internal computed `newsize = strsize + (strsize >= width
 ? width - 1 : strsize)`, which under-allocates by one byte and produces
 a user-controlled one-byte heap buffer overflow when the explicit width
 specifier exceeds 1024.  Replace the buggy formula with `strsize +
 (strsize >= width ? width : strsize)` at the three affected sites in
 stdio-common/vfscanf-internal.c.
 .
 Also add the upstream regression test stdio-common/tst-vfscanf-bz34008.c
 and wire it into stdio-common/Makefile.  The Debian 11 (glibc 2.31)
 Makefile predates libc_malloc_debug.so, so the test ENV is reduced to
 MALLOC_CHECK_=3 (matching the existing tst-mcheck-ENV / tst-malloc-usable-ENV
 entries in malloc/Makefile); mcheck_pedantic() in the test still catches
 the heap overwrite via the in-libc mcheck instrumentation.
Origin: backport, https://sourceware.org/git/?p=glibc.git;a=commit;h=839898777226a3ed88c0859f25ffe712519b4ead
Bug: https://sourceware.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=34008
Bug-Debian: https://bugs.debian.org/1134543
Author: Rocket Ma <marocketbd@gmail.com>
Last-Update: 2026-06-19

--- a/stdio-common/vfscanf-internal.c
+++ b/stdio-common/vfscanf-internal.c
@@ -804,8 +804,7 @@ __vfscanf_internal (FILE *s, const char *format, va_list argptr,
 			{
 			  /* Enlarge the buffer.  */
 			  size_t newsize
-			    = strsize
-			      + (strsize >= width ? width - 1 : strsize);
+			    = strsize + (strsize >= width ? width : strsize);

 			  str = (char *) realloc (*strptr, newsize);
 			  if (str == NULL)
@@ -876,7 +875,7 @@ __vfscanf_internal (FILE *s, const char *format, va_list argptr,
 		      && wstr == (wchar_t *) *strptr + strsize)
 		    {
 		      size_t newsize
-			= strsize + (strsize > width ? width - 1 : strsize);
+			= strsize + (strsize >= width ? width : strsize);
 		      /* Enlarge the buffer.  */
 		      wstr = (wchar_t *) realloc (*strptr,
 						  newsize * sizeof (wchar_t));
@@ -931,7 +930,7 @@ __vfscanf_internal (FILE *s, const char *format, va_list argptr,
 		    && wstr == (wchar_t *) *strptr + strsize)
 		  {
 		    size_t newsize
-		      = strsize + (strsize > width ? width - 1 : strsize);
+		      = strsize + (strsize >= width ? width : strsize);
 		    /* Enlarge the buffer.  */
 		    wstr = (wchar_t *) realloc (*strptr,
 						newsize * sizeof (wchar_t));
